00:56:00.040 --> 00:56:02.140
[INAUDIBLE] much
more complex than I

00:56:02.140 --> 00:56:04.180
thought it was going to be.

00:56:04.180 --> 00:56:06.910
In my experience, corporations
are willing to change.

00:56:06.910 --> 00:56:10.320
John Mackey once was
at MIT of Whole Foods,

00:56:10.320 --> 00:56:13.459
his students are giving him the
proper real hard time saying,

00:56:13.459 --> 00:56:14.500
why are you so expensive?

00:56:14.500 --> 00:56:16.630
The poor can't afford it.

00:56:16.630 --> 00:56:18.820
And his response was,
if they eat my food,

00:56:18.820 --> 00:56:20.120
they won't fall as sick.

00:56:20.120 --> 00:56:23.350
So in the long
run, they eat and I

00:56:23.350 --> 00:56:27.820
failed to convince them, though,
to not eat pork ribs and Coke

00:56:27.820 --> 00:56:30.350
and eat my food, so
I admit that failure,

00:56:30.350 --> 00:56:33.940
but I'm open to any
way you can suggest.

00:56:33.940 --> 00:56:37.660
And nobody really
had a suggestion.

00:56:37.660 --> 00:56:40.120
When Doug [INAUDIBLE]
of Whole Foods--

00:56:40.120 --> 00:56:47.490
of Trader Joe's came, he has
started something here called,

00:56:47.490 --> 00:56:49.450
I think, Daily Table.

00:56:49.450 --> 00:56:51.970
So he said, OK, how do I go
to a disadvantage [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:51.970 --> 00:56:53.110
bring the costs down?

00:56:53.110 --> 00:56:55.870
So he takes oranges and
all that are seconds--

00:56:55.870 --> 00:56:58.510
we all like perfect oranges,
so if its got a blemish on it

00:56:58.510 --> 00:57:00.890
you can buy it cheaper.

00:57:00.890 --> 00:57:02.410
But the jury's still out on it.

00:57:02.410 --> 00:57:03.560
Its a nonprofit.

00:57:03.560 --> 00:57:05.730
Its soaked up a lot of money.

00:57:05.730 --> 00:57:10.210
[INAUDIBLE] ultimately every
corporation I talked to says,

00:57:10.210 --> 00:57:14.560
I cannot convince the Americans
to ask for price first--

00:57:14.560 --> 00:57:16.840
the cheapest banana, the
cheapest chicken-- so

00:57:16.840 --> 00:57:19.750
what do you want me to
do as a corporation?

00:57:19.750 --> 00:57:21.860
You have an answer to that?

00:57:21.860 --> 00:57:24.410
- Well, there's a few
things I want to say.

00:57:24.410 --> 00:57:27.400
First of all, I do want
to say that corporations

00:57:27.400 --> 00:57:30.140
are paying attention to
sustainability issues

00:57:30.140 --> 00:57:31.380
as well-- oh, sorry.

00:57:31.380 --> 00:57:33.520
Corporations are paying
attention to sustainability

00:57:33.520 --> 00:57:34.250
issues as well.

00:57:34.250 --> 00:57:37.530
I have a friend here--

00:57:37.530 --> 00:57:39.730
she's visiting here
at Harvard this year--

00:57:39.730 --> 00:57:43.360
who's working on corporate
sustainability initiatives.

00:57:43.360 --> 00:57:45.440
But they are dragged
kicking and screaming.

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:47.920
I mean, they're not doing
that out of the goodness

00:57:47.920 --> 00:57:48.610
of their hearts.

00:57:48.610 --> 00:57:50.410
I mean, John
Mackey, when I first

00:57:50.410 --> 00:57:52.430
doing my research
on organics 20,

00:57:52.430 --> 00:57:55.210
25 years ago, he was
quoted as saying,

00:57:55.210 --> 00:57:58.480
since when is this movement
about social justice?

00:57:58.480 --> 00:58:05.160
But even though
corporations are maybe

00:58:05.160 --> 00:58:07.630
being paying
attention to prices,

00:58:07.630 --> 00:58:11.020
this is the problem with
food and agriculture

00:58:11.020 --> 00:58:13.690
is that people talk
about the three

00:58:13.690 --> 00:58:16.360
pillars of sustainability-- or I
would say the three things that

00:58:16.360 --> 00:58:16.930
undermine it.

00:58:16.930 --> 00:58:20.170
But you have environmental
sustainability here,

00:58:20.170 --> 00:58:24.010
you have farmer incomes here,
you have labor issues here,

00:58:24.010 --> 00:58:27.160
and you have consumer access
and accessibility here.

00:58:27.160 --> 00:58:29.530
These things are
not well aligned.

00:58:29.530 --> 00:58:31.690
They are in tension
with each other.

00:58:31.690 --> 00:58:33.430
And in my opinion,
the only thing

00:58:33.430 --> 00:58:38.890
that can kind of make it all
work out is state involvement.

00:58:38.890 --> 00:58:42.970
Because if you have cheaper
prices for consumers,

00:58:42.970 --> 00:58:46.450
then you have poorer conditions
and poorer wages for workers.

00:58:46.450 --> 00:58:49.430
But none of those things, even
that whatever has happened,

00:58:49.430 --> 00:58:53.130
none of those things have
happened without fights--

00:58:53.130 --> 00:58:55.660
and that's precisely
the point is consumers

00:58:55.660 --> 00:58:58.960
complain in more collectively.

00:58:58.960 --> 00:59:00.890
But you know, Trader
Joe's is a tough one.

00:59:00.890 --> 00:59:03.440
I mean Taylor Farms is one
of their main suppliers.

00:59:03.440 --> 00:59:05.530
I think Trader Joe's--

00:59:05.530 --> 00:59:11.170
their supply chain is not one
that we would want to emulate.

00:59:11.170 --> 00:59:12.680
There's a reason
the food is really,

00:59:12.680 --> 00:59:14.510
really cheap at Trader Joe's.

00:59:14.510 --> 00:59:18.410
And the milk they supply comes--

00:59:18.410 --> 00:59:20.110
it's organic milk
but it's coming

00:59:20.110 --> 00:59:23.290
from farms with huge feed lots.

00:59:23.290 --> 00:59:25.990
And that farm,
it's Aurora Dairy--

00:59:25.990 --> 00:59:27.120
it's more than one farm.

00:59:27.120 --> 00:59:30.820
Aurora Dairy is likely to lose
its organic certification--

00:59:30.820 --> 00:59:32.903
so I hear.

00:59:32.903 --> 00:59:33.403
Yeah?

00:59:37.740 --> 00:59:41.910
- Hi, my name's [INAUDIBLE],,
