- Well, that merger
is distressing to me

01:00:10.470 --> 01:00:18.870
because, you know, I'm not
a small is better person.

01:00:18.870 --> 01:00:21.420
I actually think that
super small businesses

01:00:21.420 --> 01:00:22.590
work at some disadvantage.

01:00:22.590 --> 01:00:24.630
I think that there's
some ways in which

01:00:24.630 --> 01:00:27.660
if we looked at more
mid-scale operations

01:00:27.660 --> 01:00:30.150
we could do more of this
collective buying practices.

01:00:30.150 --> 01:00:35.220
But any corporation that big,
of Amazon and Whole Foods,

01:00:35.220 --> 01:00:36.960
is a really frightening
thought to me.

01:00:41.190 --> 01:00:43.860
You know, the accessibility
thing with Whole Foods,

01:00:43.860 --> 01:00:46.080
it's another one of these
double-edged swords.

01:00:46.080 --> 01:00:48.510
And this goes back to this
other question before--

01:00:48.510 --> 01:00:54.810
I once walked into the Whole
Foods in Berkeley, California

01:00:54.810 --> 01:01:00.270
and there was a handwritten sign
on the cash register that says,

01:01:00.270 --> 01:01:03.377
bring in your
damage canned goods

01:01:03.377 --> 01:01:05.460
and we'll give it to the
Alameda County Food Bank.

01:01:05.460 --> 01:01:08.230
And I'm like, wait a minute.

01:01:08.230 --> 01:01:12.090
So we're shopping here
at Whole Foods and, like,

01:01:12.090 --> 01:01:15.247
the poor people get our damage,
non-organic goods at the food--

01:01:15.247 --> 01:01:17.580
I mean, there's something
fundamentally wrong with this.

01:01:17.580 --> 01:01:19.650
Some of the kind of
food recovery efforts

01:01:19.650 --> 01:01:21.960
really disturb me,
because it's, again,

01:01:21.960 --> 01:01:26.010
reinforcing that the wealthy and
privilege and the well-located

01:01:26.010 --> 01:01:28.590
get the good stuff and everybody
else gets the handouts.

01:01:28.590 --> 01:01:31.220
And there's something
fundamentally wrong with that.

01:01:31.220 --> 01:01:32.200
So that's my reaction.

