fan out about
people, but you were

01:01:43.890 --> 01:01:46.420
saying about your
writing has really

01:01:46.420 --> 01:01:48.630
informed a lot of
activists and Weighing

01:01:48.630 --> 01:01:51.900
In is probably the most
marked book on my bookshelf,

01:01:51.900 --> 01:01:53.680
has held dear to me.

01:01:53.680 --> 01:01:55.770
And I started
reading this new book

01:01:55.770 --> 01:01:59.402
and I do highly recommend it, so
I'll shamelessly plug for you.

01:01:59.402 --> 01:02:01.680
- Aw, thank you.

01:02:01.680 --> 01:02:05.850
- And one thing that I see in
your writing to some extent,

01:02:05.850 --> 01:02:08.430
but I think I'm
still grappling with

01:02:08.430 --> 01:02:11.460
and I'm wondering if you
have some ideas about,

01:02:11.460 --> 01:02:16.230
is that I think there's also an
element of self gratification

01:02:16.230 --> 01:02:18.090
with food activism.

01:02:18.090 --> 01:02:20.700
You know, we want to buy a
product and feel good about it

01:02:20.700 --> 01:02:22.440
because and that's
something we'll

01:02:22.440 --> 01:02:25.110
enjoy but then it's
also something that's

01:02:25.110 --> 01:02:27.750
saving the world, or we want
to donate to the food bank

01:02:27.750 --> 01:02:31.050
because that's easy and
we can feel good about it.

01:02:31.050 --> 01:02:32.789
But it's not that
lasting change.

01:02:32.789 --> 01:02:34.580
And I think with a lot
of social movements,

01:02:34.580 --> 01:02:36.180
instead of challenges,
you're going

01:02:36.180 --> 01:02:41.430
to have to grapple with
questions of white power.

01:02:41.430 --> 01:02:43.937
You have to grapple
with your own privilege.

01:02:43.937 --> 01:02:45.770
And you have to get out
of that comfort zone

01:02:45.770 --> 01:02:47.910
to then go into that
political sphere, which

01:02:47.910 --> 01:02:50.130
I think a lot of people
have a hard time doing,

01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:54.840
or they find that that
easy answer checks off

01:02:54.840 --> 01:02:57.690
enough of that mental
checklist in their brain

01:02:57.690 --> 01:03:01.340
that they don't have to move
into that political sphere.

01:03:01.340 --> 01:03:04.190
- Yeah, I think it's a
really, really tough question.

01:03:04.190 --> 01:03:06.170
And I grapple with it
personally all the time.

01:03:06.170 --> 01:03:08.609
I know somebody's going to
ask me if I eat organic food

01:03:08.609 --> 01:03:11.150
and buy it-- and somebody will
ask me that, so I'll just say,

01:03:11.150 --> 01:03:12.800
yes, I do.

01:03:12.800 --> 01:03:16.410
And I just think that, as
I was telling my students,

01:03:16.410 --> 01:03:18.540
sometimes you have to
live with contradiction.

01:03:18.540 --> 01:03:20.581
But I think that there's
something about the food

01:03:20.581 --> 01:03:22.710
movement in particular that--

01:03:22.710 --> 01:03:25.790
well, we know what it is about
the food because food is what?

01:03:25.790 --> 01:03:26.360
Sustenance.

01:03:26.360 --> 01:03:27.545
And food is pleasure.

01:03:27.545 --> 01:03:29.420
So there's something
about that food movement

01:03:29.420 --> 01:03:32.030
where that contradiction
comes to a head.

01:03:32.030 --> 01:03:37.070
I mean, while it may be fun to--

01:03:37.070 --> 01:03:40.610
oh, I have I still have Black
Lives Matter on the screen;

01:03:40.610 --> 01:03:42.710
you have strawberries.

01:03:42.710 --> 01:03:47.417
It may be fun to attend
a rally or a march--

01:03:47.417 --> 01:03:50.000
which may or may not be all that
effective, but it may be fun,

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:52.052
but it's not what's
motivating you.

01:03:52.052 --> 01:03:54.260
But with food movements
that's what's motivating you,

01:03:54.260 --> 01:03:56.343
and I think that's why so
much food movements have

01:03:56.343 --> 01:04:00.350
been about teaching people
how to eat because, oh, I

01:04:00.350 --> 01:04:03.920
have the pleasures of eating
like Alice Waters of Chez

01:04:03.920 --> 01:04:06.290
Panisse tells me to
with my organic kale

01:04:06.290 --> 01:04:09.080
with lots of garlic
and salt and olive oil.

01:04:09.080 --> 01:04:11.000
So let me teach
you about it, too.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:12.720
Let me share the
pleasure with you.

01:04:12.720 --> 01:04:15.770
And I think that it's
because of the food

01:04:15.770 --> 01:04:18.680
itself that kind of
gets the movement

01:04:18.680 --> 01:04:23.167
into that very contradictory
place of pleasure and action.

01:04:23.167 --> 01:04:25.250
And I don't know that
there's any way around that.

01:04:28.680 --> 01:04:30.020
But I do think it's unique.

01:04:30.020 --> 01:04:33.371
And I don't know if that
gets to your question, but--

01:04:33.371 --> 01:04:34.302
- Good effort.

01:04:34.302 --> 01:04:34.802
- OK.

01:04:38.120 --> 01:04:38.620
- Hi.

01:04:38.620 --> 01:04:40.160
Thank you so much for speaking.

01:04:40.160 --> 01:04:42.610
I wanted to pick up
on a point that you'd

01:04:42.610 --> 01:04:44.770
made earlier about how
some of your students

01:04:44.770 --> 01:04:48.970
have this tendency to want to
go out and teach poor people how

01:04:48.970 --> 01:04:53.650
to cook, which might be
well intentioned but sort

01:04:53.650 --> 01:04:54.550
of misguided.

01:04:54.550 --> 01:04:57.130
And I wanted to get your
thoughts on something,

01:04:57.130 --> 01:05:02.530
because I do think that people
of all economic backgrounds

01:05:02.530 --> 01:05:05.800
do rely too much on
processed food, fast food,

01:05:05.800 --> 01:05:08.290
and it's detrimental
to everyone's health.

01:05:08.290 --> 01:05:11.020
I think it can also be
detrimental to our sense

01:05:11.020 --> 01:05:14.380
of culture and just general
empowerment in your life.

01:05:14.380 --> 01:05:16.900
And I think that
a lot that you can

01:05:16.900 --> 01:05:19.240
trace that back to
systemic issues--

01:05:19.240 --> 01:05:21.940
we phased out home ec
in schools, for example.

01:05:21.940 --> 01:05:23.740
And so I guess
I'm just wondering

01:05:23.740 --> 01:05:26.890
if you have thoughts
on how to address sort

01:05:26.890 --> 01:05:29.770
of the cooking side
of it from more

01:05:29.770 --> 01:05:32.920
of a systemic issue
instead of just these,

01:05:32.920 --> 01:05:36.160
let's do little workshops and
teach poor people how to cook.

01:05:36.160 --> 01:05:41.725
- Yeah, no, that's another
kind of a biting question here.

01:05:41.725 --> 01:05:43.010
I was at a--

01:05:43.010 --> 01:05:43.750
I'm sorry.

01:05:43.750 --> 01:05:45.625
All these stories keep
popping into my brain.

01:05:45.625 --> 01:05:47.385
But I was at this book
fair in Los Angeles

01:05:47.385 --> 01:05:48.760
and I was speaking
about my book.

01:05:48.760 --> 01:05:51.974
And there was an
author of a cookbook.

01:05:51.974 --> 01:05:53.890
She says, if all we need
to do is teach people

01:05:53.890 --> 01:05:55.710
how to make vinaigrette.

01:06:01.181 --> 01:06:03.280
The cooking thing is an
interesting one, right?

01:06:03.280 --> 01:06:04.696
And Michael Pollan
and others have

01:06:04.696 --> 01:06:09.610
written about that we
need to get kind of back

01:06:09.610 --> 01:06:11.840
to the kitchen.

01:06:11.840 --> 01:06:15.490
And I like cooking.

01:06:15.490 --> 01:06:16.570
Cooking's a good thing.

01:06:16.570 --> 01:06:20.060
But I still think
there's this fun--

01:06:20.060 --> 01:06:21.490
why do people not cook?

01:06:21.490 --> 01:06:23.680
Maybe they love the
Jack in the Box,

01:06:23.680 --> 01:06:26.590
but I mean when you
have people with two

01:06:26.590 --> 01:06:29.420
jobs or single parents,
they're picking up their--

01:06:29.420 --> 01:06:33.640
I mean, let's get real here
about the cooking thing.

01:06:33.640 --> 01:06:37.750
So I think it's nice to cook.

01:06:37.750 --> 01:06:41.600
I'd like to-- ultimately I
think people could eat more

01:06:41.600 --> 01:06:44.080
nutritiously and
possibly cheaper--

01:06:44.080 --> 01:06:46.420
not super cheap with
cooking, but you

01:06:46.420 --> 01:06:51.010
have to face the real
obstacles to cooking.

01:06:51.010 --> 01:06:52.960
But I think that's
a different issue

01:06:52.960 --> 01:06:55.570
than like this kind of
proselytizing about cooking,

01:06:55.570 --> 01:06:58.390
and for me that when my
students are picking up

01:06:58.390 --> 01:07:02.530
on that is that it's been more
that they can't imagine what

01:07:02.530 --> 01:07:04.690
else is possible to
change the food system.

01:07:04.690 --> 01:07:07.276
Now they can more,
but that's where

01:07:07.276 --> 01:07:08.775
they were about 10
years ago-- well,

01:07:08.775 --> 01:07:09.983
what else are we going to do?

01:07:09.983 --> 01:07:12.280
I go, well, look, here's
this great organization that

01:07:12.280 --> 01:07:14.740
does great anti-pesticide work.

01:07:14.740 --> 01:07:16.545
Well, I don't want
to sit behind a desk.

01:07:16.545 --> 01:07:17.920
I don't want to
be in a computer.

01:07:17.920 --> 01:07:21.901
So sometimes that
pleasure really can--

01:07:21.901 --> 01:07:22.400
excuse me.

01:07:22.400 --> 01:07:23.816
Something that
pleasure can really

01:07:23.816 --> 01:07:27.422
get in the way of
what's important.

01:07:27.422 --> 01:07:31.300
I mean, if we think of other
kind of important moments

01:07:31.300 --> 01:07:32.230
of our time--

01:07:32.230 --> 01:07:35.140
important activism,
you wouldn't--

01:07:35.140 --> 01:07:38.740
I'm just trying to think of
some analogous situation.

01:07:38.740 --> 01:07:41.760
If you were concerned about
Syrian refugees, for example,

01:07:41.760 --> 01:07:43.177
you wouldn't--

01:07:43.177 --> 01:07:45.760
I can't think of the analogous
situation where we'd say, well,

01:07:45.760 --> 01:07:48.544
I want to do this
because it's more fun.

01:07:48.544 --> 01:07:50.710
So, again, there's something
about the food movement

01:07:50.710 --> 01:07:52.720
that puts us in that, well,
I want to just have fun

01:07:52.720 --> 01:07:53.620
while I'm doing this.

01:07:57.220 --> 01:07:57.790
- Hi.

01:07:57.790 --> 01:07:59.790
My name's Rachel and I'm
a student at the School

01:07:59.790 --> 01:08:00.910
of Public Health here.

01:08:00.910 --> 01:08:03.730
And I had a question on--

01:08:03.730 --> 01:08:06.730
you described the current
pessimistic political climate

01:08:06.730 --> 01:08:08.950
and also a lot about
what bothers you what

01:08:08.950 --> 01:08:10.840
people do around food activism.

01:08:10.840 --> 01:08:12.640
But, under the
assumption that everybody

01:08:12.640 --> 01:08:15.070
here is interested
in food activism

01:08:15.070 --> 01:08:18.490
and wants to take
action, what do

01:08:18.490 --> 01:08:21.960
you recommend as next steps
for when we leave this room?

01:08:21.960 --> 01:08:23.500
Like, is there
anything concrete you

01:08:23.500 --> 01:08:26.920
can think of to do in our daily
lives that would really help?

01:08:26.920 --> 01:08:28.720
- Well, you know there are--

01:08:28.720 --> 01:08:30.700
not many-- but there
are good organizations

01:08:30.700 --> 01:08:37.060
that do good work, organizations
that do pesticide activism.

01:08:37.060 --> 01:08:40.160
Some Some of them have
letter writing campaigns.

01:08:40.160 --> 01:08:42.410
You can join one of those
and get on their ListServes.

01:08:42.410 --> 01:08:47.410
It's always better to
write individual notes

01:08:47.410 --> 01:08:51.069
than just do the
clicktivism, but, you know.

01:08:51.069 --> 01:08:54.010
Like, for instance, right
now Pesticide Action Network

01:08:54.010 --> 01:09:01.279
is working hard to put that
chlorpyrifos ban back in place.

01:09:01.279 --> 01:09:03.580
So you have to get
on the ListServes.

01:09:03.580 --> 01:09:04.819
You have to write letters.

01:09:04.819 --> 01:09:07.189
But it worked on this
methyl iodide campaign.

01:09:07.189 --> 01:09:08.830
So that's one place you can go.

01:09:08.830 --> 01:09:11.500
The Farm Bill should
be coming up soon,

01:09:11.500 --> 01:09:15.189
and I expect to see the
Trump Administration come up

01:09:15.189 --> 01:09:17.680
with a really nasty one.

01:09:17.680 --> 01:09:20.080
And there will be
many organizations

01:09:20.080 --> 01:09:22.970
that will be working on that.

01:09:22.970 --> 01:09:26.260
So whether you only
can write your letter--

01:09:26.260 --> 01:09:31.029
but an individualized letter--
or give $100, that's something.

01:09:31.029 --> 01:09:33.939
Or if you're a
student and you're

01:09:33.939 --> 01:09:37.870
looking to employ
yourself later,

01:09:37.870 --> 01:09:40.359
you can intern and
get involved and work.

01:09:40.359 --> 01:09:44.620
But those things do exist.

01:09:44.620 --> 01:09:47.799
Or working on--
there's so many--

01:09:50.740 --> 01:09:53.529
how you work on immigration
reform is a tough one, right?

01:09:53.529 --> 01:09:57.600
I mean, whether you're
immigration reform

01:09:57.600 --> 01:09:59.520
or immigration, whether
you're like leaving

01:09:59.520 --> 01:10:05.340
plastic jugs of water in the
desert in Arizona or, again,

01:10:05.340 --> 01:10:10.030
lobbying your congressperson
about a safer,

01:10:10.030 --> 01:10:12.250
better immigration bill,
those are different options.

01:10:12.250 --> 01:10:13.440
But there's lots.

01:10:13.440 --> 01:10:17.749
But they're not always
as tangibly about food,

01:10:17.749 --> 01:10:19.290
and I think that's
one of the things,

01:10:19.290 --> 01:10:23.040
too, is that the policies that
I think impinge on the food

01:10:23.040 --> 01:10:25.740
system are not always
about that material thing

01:10:25.740 --> 01:10:28.380
called food-- they're about
the systems that are around it.

01:10:31.950 --> 01:10:33.442
- Hi-- oh, sorry.

01:10:33.442 --> 01:10:34.650
I'm [? Nicole ?] [INAUDIBLE].

01:10:34.650 --> 01:10:38.000
I'm a Harvard Extension
Sustainability Master's

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:44.580
student, and my question, or
two of our biggest global issues

01:10:44.580 --> 01:10:48.369
is soil security and soil
fertility, as well as the food

01:10:48.369 --> 01:10:49.410
waste that we throw away.

01:10:49.410 --> 01:10:54.040
So in developed countries we're
sending about 40% to landfill.

01:10:54.040 --> 01:10:56.490
So my question is, is
there or should there

01:10:56.490 --> 01:10:58.680
be discussions
around a to cradle

01:10:58.680 --> 01:11:02.250
to grave initiative for
the agriculture sector,

01:11:02.250 --> 01:11:04.020
and does this present
any opportunities

01:11:04.020 --> 01:11:05.730
to resolve any of the
issues that you've

01:11:05.730 --> 01:11:06.840
discussed with us today?

01:11:19.310 --> 01:11:22.700
- Food waste is a tricky one.

01:11:22.700 --> 01:11:26.540
I think food waste is a
huge aesthetic problem--

01:11:26.540 --> 01:11:30.080
no one likes to see food waste.

01:11:30.080 --> 01:11:32.720
Most of the food waste--

01:11:32.720 --> 01:11:35.010
and this isn't answering
your question directly,

01:11:35.010 --> 01:11:36.470
it's just what I know about--

01:11:36.470 --> 01:11:37.940
most of the food
waste initiatives

01:11:37.940 --> 01:11:39.500
are really geared
toward consumers,

01:11:39.500 --> 01:11:42.170
like, here's how to
reuse that or use

01:11:42.170 --> 01:11:44.720
that kale that's been
sitting there in your door

01:11:44.720 --> 01:11:47.000
for three weeks.

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:51.140
Most of the food waste occurs
in agricultural production--

01:11:51.140 --> 01:11:53.260
and lots of it.

01:11:53.260 --> 01:11:57.520
And it's-- yes, there are
organizations that do food

01:11:57.520 --> 01:12:03.800
recovery, whether it's
organizing gleaning.

01:12:03.800 --> 01:12:10.690
But our food production system
is geared to create food waste.

01:12:10.690 --> 01:12:13.510
It's profitable to
create food waste.

01:12:13.510 --> 01:12:18.760
So, again, it's a matter
of figure out ways

01:12:18.760 --> 01:12:23.320
to address how food is
produced through policy

01:12:23.320 --> 01:12:27.520
and through somehow changing
up the incentives so

01:12:27.520 --> 01:12:28.545
corporate farming--

01:12:28.545 --> 01:12:29.920
it's not only
corporate farming--

01:12:29.920 --> 01:12:33.220
individual farmers
just don't leave

01:12:33.220 --> 01:12:36.160
so much food on the field.

01:12:36.160 --> 01:12:39.190
But, you know,
your question also

01:12:39.190 --> 01:12:41.710
brings us to bigger
questions about,

01:12:41.710 --> 01:12:44.620
what is the nature of hunger?

01:12:44.620 --> 01:12:46.990
And if it's about
insufficient food production.

01:12:46.990 --> 01:12:51.490
I'm concerned about food
waste because you don't

01:12:51.490 --> 01:12:53.060
want to see soil go to waste.

01:12:53.060 --> 01:12:59.230
You don't want to see animal
lives put down for nothing.

01:12:59.230 --> 01:13:02.710
But I'm always worried
about food recovery

01:13:02.710 --> 01:13:04.000
as a way to address it.

01:13:04.000 --> 01:13:06.870
And that's about as much as
I can say about at this point

01:13:06.870 --> 01:13:08.870
because it's not something
I've looked at a lot.

